<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-22T12:41:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-22T12:41:00-05:00" n="547" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d547">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/482</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Garrett</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-22T19:00:00+01:19">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 22, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 23, 8.37
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2828. I had an informal conversation with the Minister for Foreign
                                Affairs today on the subject of your 1222, May 20, 6 p.m. He says he
                                will consult his experts and let me know in a day or two as
                                definitely as he can when Dutch ships may be expected to arrive to
                                lift grain. He added that <persName>Gevers</persName><note n="1" xml:id="d547fn1">Netherland Minister in Germany.</note> informed
                                him this morning from Berlin that the two ships to replace <hi rend="italic">Juno</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Stella</hi> would
                                probably get German permits without trouble, and <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1">Loudon</persName> professes
                                to be only waiting to hear from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_DBWH1">Beaufort</persName> that <hi rend="italic">Juno</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Stella</hi> have
                                received their clearance papers before despatching these replacing
                                ships. This also applied to <hi rend="italic">Frisia</hi>, which I
                                learn from another source is to replace <hi rend="italic">Hollandia</hi>. See your 1170, May 8, 6 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d547fn2">Not printed.</note>
                                <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1">Loudon</persName>
                                intimated that Germany is making conditions which will prevent the
                                despatch of more than a few Dutch ships.</p>
                            <p>Could you advise me how soon <hi rend="italic">Juno</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Stella</hi> are expected to leave?</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>